  1. How many diamonds are 0.99 carat? How many are 1 carat? What do you think is the cause of the difference?
diamonds %>%
  count(carat == 0.99)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   `carat == 0.99`     n
##             <lgl> <int>
## 1           FALSE 53917
## 2            TRUE    23
diamonds %>%
  count(carat ==1.00)
## # A tibble: 2 x 2
##   `carat == 1`     n
##          <lgl> <int>
## 1        FALSE 52382
## 2         TRUE  1558

Only 23 diamonds in this dataset weigh 0.99 carat, but more than 1500 diamonds are exactly 1.00 carat. I think people have a strong preference/there is a big demand for 1.00 carat diamonds.

  1. Compare and contrast coord_cartesian() vs xlim() or ylim() when zooming in on a histogram. What happens if you leave binwidth unset? What happens if you try and zoom so only half a bar shows?
ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = price)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) +
  coord_cartesian(xlim = c(1000,2000))

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = price), xlim = c(1000,2000)) +
  geom_histogram(binwidth = 10) #I have no idea what this xlim did. 

ggplot(data = diamonds, mapping = aes(x = price), xlim = c(1000,2000)) +
